<ref name=\"Byron Allen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|title=Byron Allen Acquires The Weather Group in $300 Million Deal|last=Albiniak|first=Paige|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322203251/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|archive-date=March 22, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Entertainment Studios, Inc.''' is an American media and entertainment company based in [[Los Angeles]]. Owned and founded in 1993 by African-American comedian [[Byron Allen]], the company was initially involved in the production and distribution of first-run television series for [[United States|U.S.]] [[Broadcast syndication|television syndication]]. Under the [[Entertainment Studios Networks]] division, it also operates a group of [[digital cable]] and [[satellite television|satellite]] channels, which broadcast a mix of original programs and the company's syndicated content.\n\nIn the late 2010s, the company made several major expansions to its operations, including entering the [[film distribution]] market, acquiring [[The Weather Channel]] from [[NBCUniversal]] and [[Bain Capital]], partnering with [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] to acquire the [[regional sports network]] chain [[Fox Sports Networks]], and its acquisition of television stations from another minority-owned media group, [[Bayou City Broadcasting]].\n\n==History==\nEntertainment Studios was founded in 1993<ref name=dl2>{{cite news|last=Busch |first=Anita |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/byron-allen-acquires-indie-distribution-co-freestyle-releasing-1201591215/ |title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Acquires Indie Freestyle Releasing |publisher=Deadline |date=2015-10-22 |accessdate=2017-10-03}}</ref> as '''CF Entertainment''' by [[Byron Allen]].<ref name=bc>{{cite news |last1=Albiniak |first1=By Paige |title=CF Entertainment Gets New Name |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/cf-entertainment-gets-new-name-77234 |accessdate=October 5, 2019 |work=Broadcasting & Cable |date=December 12, 2003 |language=en-us}}</ref> The company was initially focused on producing low-cost, syndicated non-fiction programming, including interview series and [[court show]]s (largely scripted from actual testimony). Allen serves as host for some of these programs.<ref name=\"vty1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-still-very-acquisitive-1203117363/|title=Byron Allen Is Still 'Very Acquisitive' After Transformative Year|last=Marich|first=Robert|date=January 25, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> In December 2003, CF became Entertainment Studios.<ref name=bc/>\n\nEntertainment Studios greenlit its first film and stage projects in December 2011, when it acquired the rights to develop a [[biographical film]] and [[Play (theatre)|theatrical play]] on the life of [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]] from Davis' daughter with actor/singer, [[Tracey Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sammy-davis-jr-byron-allen-271544|title=Sammy Davis Jr. Biopic, Stage Show Planned|last=Block|first=Alex|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe company ventured into scripted programming in 2012, with the third-quarter launch of the sitcoms ''[[Mr. Box Office]]'' and ''[[The First Family (TV series)|The First Family]]''.<ref name=\"dl3\">{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Clears Syndicated Sitcom Block For Fall '12 Launch|url=http://deadline.com/2012/05/byron-allens-entertainment-studios-clears-syndicated-sitcom-block-for-fall-12-launch-276052/|accessdate=October 12, 2017|work=Deadline|date=May 21, 2012}}</ref> Both are set for 104 episodes<ref name=\"dl3\" /> over two years under a model of accelerated production similar to [[Debmar-Mercury]]'s [[Debmar-Mercury#The 10-90 Model|10-90 Model]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Comedy Series Starring Bill Bellamy Eying 100-Episode Order, Fall Launch|url=http://deadline.com/2012/05/comedy-series-starring-bill-bellamy-eying-100-episode-order-fall-launch-264598/|accessdate=October 12, 2017|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 3, 2012}}</ref> The two half hour shows were picked up as a two-hour weekend primetime [[programming block]] with two episodes of each show back to back by [[Tribune Broadcasting|Tribune]], [[Weigel Broadcasting|Weigel]] and [[CBS Television Stations|CBS Television Station]] groups.<ref name=\"dl3\" /> The company launched its eighth cable channel and first ad-supported service, Justice Central.TV, on December 10, 2012.<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite web|last=Block|first=Alex Ben|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Launches Legal Digital Network|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/byron-allen-s-entertainment-studios-399843|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Entertainment Studios acquired [[Freestyle Releasing]] for an undisclosed amount \"said to be sealed for high-eight figures\". Freestyle also had an output deal with [[Netflix]].<ref name=dl2/> The Freestyle purchase was used to bolster an expansion into [[Film distributor|film distribution]], via its new Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures division.<ref name=\"wrap\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thewrap.com/inside-historic-sundance-bidding-war-for-birth-of-a-nation-why-netflix-offered-more-but-still-lost/|title=Inside Sundance Bidding War for 'Birth of a Nation'|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|date=January 26, 2016|work=The Wrap|accessdate=October 4, 2017|last2=Waxman|first2=Sharon}}</ref><ref name=\"HostilesInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/hostiles-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-47-meters-down-eddie-murphy-bob-weinstein-1202236594/|title='Hostiles' Distributor Byron Allen, On Growing A Movie Company In Difficult Times For Indies|last=Fleming|first=Mike|date=January 5, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> Its first release, ''[[47 Meters Down]]'', took in $44 million in box office revenue.<ref name=\"vty1\"/>\n\nAcross 2015, the company separately sued [[AT&T]], [[Comcast]] and [[Charter Communications]] for racial discrimination in being biased against minority run entertainment companies in not carrying its cable channels. AT&T settled in December with the addition of 7 of Entertainment Studios' channels added to AT&T's DirecTV line up. Entertainment Studios added similar suits against Charter and the FCC.<ref>{{cite news|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Files $10 Billion Discrimination Lawsuit Against Charter Communications, FCC|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-10-billion-discrimination-lawsuit-charter-fcc-1201691330/|accessdate=October 3, 2017|work=Variety|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref> The Comcast case, though initially dismissed at the district court, was allowed to go forward by the Ninth Circuit; Comcast was able to successfully petition the Supreme Court to hear its case in ''[[Comcast v. National Association of African-American-Owned Media]]'' during November 2019. The Charter case, also allowed to proceed by the Ninth Circuit, still has its petition pending at the Supreme Court.\n\nIn June 2016, Entertainment Studios acquired [[TheGrio]], a news website focusing on stories of interest to African Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/entertainment-studios-acquires-thegrio-1201772993/|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Acquires TheGrio, African-American Focused Digital News Platform|last=Evans|first=Greg|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 15, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> In mid-September 2017, the company announced plans to launch an [[Over-the-top content|over the top]] sports streaming service known as Sports.tv.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lafayette|first=Jon|title=Entertainment Studios to Launch Streaming OTT Sports Platform|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/entertainment-studios-launch-streaming-ott-sports-platform/168737|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2018, Entertainment Studios announced its intent to acquire [[The Weather Channel]]'s television assets from an [[NBCUniversal]]/[[Bain Capital]]/[[Blackstone Group]] partnership. The actual value was undisclosed, but was reported to be around $300 million; the channel's [[The Weather Company|non-television assets]], which were separately sold to IBM two years prior, were not included in the sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|title=Byron Allen Acquires The Weather Group in $300 Million Deal|last=Albiniak|first=Paige|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322203251/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|archive-date=March 22, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Entertainment Studios announced that it had arranged $500 million worth of [[Line of credit|credit facilities]] through [[Deutsche Bank]] Securities, Jefferies Financial Group, Brightwood Capital Advisors and [[Comerica]]. Allen explained that these funds were to be used for further \"large-scale\" acquisitions, productions, and other general expenses.<ref name=\"vty1\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Byron Allen Announces $500M In Credit Facility For Entertainment Studios Expansion|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-500-million-credit-facilities-expansion-1202456572/|accessdate=September 17, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 4, 2018}}</ref> In an interview with ''Variety'', Allen stated that he was \"not a seller\", and that he was \"one or two acquisitions away from being a fairly large company\".<ref name=\"vty1\"/> On May 3, 2019, it was announced that, under the subsidiary Diamond Sports Group, Entertainment Studios would be an equity and content partner in [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]'s acquisition of [[Fox Sports Networks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/sinclair-disney-regional-sports-network-deal-1203204685/|title=Sinclair Clinches Disney-Regional Sports Networks Deal, Byron Allen Joins as Partner|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=May 3, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn May 6, 2019, Entertainment Studios announced that it would expand into television station ownership by acquiring the stations of [[Bayou City Broadcasting]] for $165 million, including Evansville, Indiana's [[WEVV-TV]] and [[WEEV-LD]], and Lafayette, Louisiana's [[KADN-TV]] and [[KLAF-LD]]. The stations will operate under the new unit, Allen Media Broadcasting.<ref name=vty0>{{cite web|last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |title=Byron Allen Expands Into Broadcasting, Buys 4 TV Stations for $165 Million |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/byron-allen-buys-tv-stations-165-milion-1203205894/ |accessdate=May 6, 2019|work=Variety|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> The sale was completed on July 31, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Wes |title=FCC Approves Evansville TV Station Sale |url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/story/40860316/fcc-approves-evansville-tv-station-sale |accessdate=August 8, 2019 |work=Inside Indiana Business |publisher=Grow INdiana Media Ventures, LLC |date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> On October 1, 2019, Allen Media agreed to purchase 11 stations from [[Heartland Media|USA Television]] for $290 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lafayette |first1=Jon |title=Allen\u2019s Entertainment Studios Buying USA Stations for $290M |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/allens-entertainment-studios-buying-usa-stations-for-290m |accessdate=October 1, 2019 |work=Broadcasting & Cable |publisher=Future Publishing Limited |date=October 1, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref> The sale of the Heartland stations was approved by the FCC on November 22, 2019, <ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/1810966.pdf \"Notice of Consent to Transfer of Control\"], ''CDBS Public Access'', [[Federal Communications Commission]], 22 November 2019, Retrieved 27 November 2019.</ref> and it was completed on February 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Anita |title=Byron Allen\u2019s Entertainment Studios Acquires 11 Local TV Stations For $305 Million |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/byron-allens-entertainment-studios-expands-broadcast-holdings-with-purchase-of-11-tv-stations-for-305-million-1202858008/ |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |work=Deadline |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Television series distributed by Entertainment Studios==\n===Court shows===\n*''[[America's Court with Judge Ross]]''\n*''[[Justice for All with Judge Cristina P\u00e9rez]]''\n*''[[Mablean Ephriam|Justice with Judge Mablean]]''\n*''Supreme Justice with Judge Karen''\n*''[[Glenda Hatchett|The Verdict with Judge Hatchett]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/entertainment-studios-orders-130-more-episodes-of-all-five-of-its-court-shows-1202472098/|title=Entertainment Studios Orders 130 More Episodes For Each Of Its Five Court Shows|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref> <!-- sourcing all court shows -->\n*''[[We the People With Gloria Allred]]'' (2011-2012)\n\n===Sitcoms===\n*''[[The First Family (TV series)|The First Family]]'' (September 2012\u2013April 25, 2015) syndicated (April 19, 2013\u2013 ) [[BET Her]]\n*''[[Mr. Box Office]]'' (September 2012\u2013April 25, 2015) syndicated (April 19, 2013\u2013 ) BET Her<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bet-networks-nabs-two-sitcoms-433046|title=BET Networks Nabs Two Sitcoms in Multimillion-Dollar Reverse-Syndication Deal|last=Block|first=Alex|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 4, 2013|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Game shows===\n*''[[Funny You Should Ask (2017 game show)|Funny You Should Ask]]''\n*''[[Who Wants to Date a Comedian?]]''\n\n===Syndicated specials===\n*''Comedy Jam''\n*''Feel the Beat''\n*''Happy Holidays America''\n*''We Have a Dream''\n\n===Talk and magazine series===\n*''Beautiful Homes & Great Estates''\n*''Career Day''\n*''[[Comics Unleashed with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Designers, Fashions & Runways''\n*''[[Entertainers with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Global Business People''\n*''The Gossip Queens''\n*''Latin Lifestyles''\n*''[[Kickin' It with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Urban Style''\n*''The Writer's Hot List''\n*''[[The Young Icons]]''\n\n===Other shows===\n*''[[The American Athlete]]''\n\n== Entertainment Studios Networks ==\n{{Main|Entertainment Studios Networks}}\n\n===Cable and Digital===\n*''Automotive.TV''\n*''Cars.TV''\n*''Comedy.TV''\n*''ES.TV''<ref name=\"dl1\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/anchor-bay-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-multi-year-deal-1201786756/|title=Anchor Bay And Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Join In Multi-Year Deal|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=July 14, 2016|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n*''MyDestination.TV''\n*''Pets.TV''\n*''Recipe.TV''<ref name=dl1/>\n\n===Television channels===\n*Justice Central, launched December 10, 2012 on AT&T U-verse's family tier which is also its first advertising support only channel.<ref name=thr/>\n* Weather network\n**[[The Weather Channel]]\n**[[Weatherscan]]\n**[[Local Now]]\n\n==Allen Media Broadcasting==\nAllen Media Broadcasting, LLC is a TV station operating company owned by Entertainment Studios.\n\nOn May 6, 2019, Entertainment Studios announced that it would expand into television station ownership by acquiring the stations of [[Bayou City Broadcasting]] for $165 million, including Evansville, Indiana's [[WEVV-TV]] and [[WEEV-LD]], and Lafayette, Louisiana's [[KADN-TV]] and [[KLAF-LD]]. The stations will operate under the new division Allen Media Broadcasting.<ref name=vty0/> Allen Media made an offer for [[TEGNA]] TV station group as the third know bidder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Byron Allen Makes Acquisition Offer for Tegna Station Group |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/byron-allen-tegna-acquisition-bid-1203531539/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Variety |date=March 12, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Television stations===\nStations are arranged in alphabetical order by state and [[city of license]].\n\n'''Note:'''\n* ('''##''') - ''Indicates stations that were previously owned by [[Bayou City Broadcasting]], prior to its acquisition by Allen Media in 2019.''\n* ('''\u00a7\u00a7''') - ''Indicates stations that were previously owned by [[Heartland Media]], prior to its acquisition by Allen Media in 2020.''\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| [[City of license]] / [[Media market|Market]]\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| Station\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| Channel<br>[[Virtual channel|TV]] ([[Digital terrestrial television|RF]])\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| Owned since\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| Network affiliation\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| [[Huntsville, Alabama]] \n| '''[[WAAY-TV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 31 (17)\n| 2020\n| [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Chico, California|Chico]] - [[Redding, California]]\n| '''[[KHSL-TV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 12 (36) \n| 2020\n| {{ubl|[[CBS]]|[[The CW]] (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[KNVN]]'''\n| 24 (24)\n| <sup>1</sup>\n| {{ubl|[[NBC]]|[[Telemundo]] (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Evansville, Indiana]]\n| '''[[WEVV-TV]]''' <sup>##</sup>\n| 44 (28)\n| 2015\n| {{ubl|CBS|[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]/[[MyNetworkTV]] (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WEVV-TV|WEEV-LD]]''' <sup>##</sup><br>{{small|(Repeater of WEVV-DT2)}}\n| 47 (21)\n| 2019\n| {{ubl|Fox/MyNetworkTV}} \n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n| '''[[WFFT-TV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 55 (20)\n| 2020\n| Fox\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| [[West Lafayette, Indiana]]\n| '''[[WLFI-TV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 18 (11)\n| 2020\n| {{ubl|CBS|The CW (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n| '''[[WTHI-TV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 10 (10)\n| 2020\n| {{ubl|CBS|Fox/MyNetworkTV (DT2)|The CW (DT3)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| [[Mason City, Iowa]] - [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| '''[[KIMT]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup> \n| 3 (24)\n| 2020\n| {{ubl|CBS|MyNetworkTV (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n| '''[[KADN-TV]]''' <sup>##</sup>\n| 15 (16)\n| 2019\n| {{ubl|Fox|NBC (DT2)|MyNetworkTV (DT3)}} \n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[KLAF-LD]]''' <sup>##</sup>\n| 46 (14)\n| 2019\n| NBC\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| [[Eugene, Oregon]]\n| '''[[KEZI]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 9 (9)\n| 2020\n| ABC\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]] - [[Columbus, Mississippi]]\n| '''[[WTVA]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 9 (11)\n| 2020\n| {{ubl|NBC|ABC (DT2)}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WLOV-TV]]'''\n| 27 (16)\n| <sup>2</sup>\n| Fox\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Medford, Oregon|Medford]] \u2013 [[Klamath Falls, Oregon]]\n| '''[[KDRV]]''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup>\n| 12 (12)\n| 2020\n| ABC\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''KDKF''' <sup>\u00a7\u00a7</sup><br>{{small|(Satellite of KDRV)}}\n| 31 (29)\n| 2020\n| ABC\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n|}\n\n'''Other Notes:'''\n*<sup>1</sup> Owned by Maxair Media, LLC., Allen Media operates the station under a [[Local marketing agreement|shared services agreement]] (SSA).\n*<sup>2</sup> Owned by Coastal Television Broadcasting Company LLC., Allen Media operates the station under a shared services agreement.\n\n==Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures==\nIn 2016, Entertainment Studios began to make major expansions into film distribution; at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], the company made a surprise $20 million bid for ''[[The Birth of a Nation (2016 film)|The Birth of a Nation]]'', losing to [[Fox Searchlight]].<ref name=\"wrap\" /> In July 2016, Entertainment Studios signed a multi-year home video and on-demand distribution deal with [[Anchor Bay Entertainment]], covering future theatrical releases by the company.<ref name=\"dl1\" /> The studio acquired its first film later that month, with the North American rights to ''[[47 Meters Down]]'' from [[Dimension Films]].<ref name=\"vty\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/mandy-moore-shark-tale-47-meters-down-weinsteins-1201822542/|title=Mandy Moore's Shark Tale '47 Meters Down' Bought From Weinsteins|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=25 July 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref> At the 2017 [[Toronto Film Festival]], Entertainment Studios also bought ''[[Chappaquiddick (film)|Chappaquiddick]]'', ''[[Replicas (film)|Replicas]]'', and ''[[Hostiles (film)|Hostiles]]''.<ref name=\"dl\">{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/hostiles-christian-bale-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-scott-cooper-rosamund-pike-ken-kao-oscar-season-launch-1202181081/|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Hostiles; Christian Bale-Starrer Gets Oscar Season Berth|last=Fleming|first=Mike|date=October 3, 2017|work=Deadline|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Entertainment Studios aimed to distribute at least 18 films in 2018.<ref name=\"HostilesInterview\" /> In January 2018, on his film distribution model, Allen stated:\n\n{{quote|We're chasing the studio crumbs. They don't want movies that do $40 million to $60 million. We totally will be good with those numbers, and that is what we're pursuing. Our thing is we are really big on slow roll-outs and small releases. Our philosophy &mdash; we believe in wide releases. We like to have movies that are 1,500-4,000 screens and we are chasing what the studios don't want. They're chasing much bigger. And we're going to take their crumbs and make a gourmet meal. And then eventually we'll move on to chasing more than their crumbs. But today we're chasing the crumbs.<ref name=\"HostilesInterview\"/>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Release Date !! Film title !! Director !! Gross<ref>{{cite web |title=Entertainment Studios All Time Box Office Results |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?yr=&view=company&view2=allmovies&studio=entertainmentstudios.htm&sort=open&order=ASC&p=.htm |website=BoxOfficeMojo.com |publisher=IMDb.com, Inc |accessdate=6 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2017 || June 16, 2017 ||''[[47 Meters Down]]'' || [[Johannes Roberts]] || $44.3 million || <ref name=vty/>\n|-\n| September 22, 2017 || ''[[Friend Request]]'' || [[Simon Verhoeven]] || $3.7 million || <ref>{{cite news|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=Freestyle Releasing Gets 'Friend Request'|url=http://deadline.com/2016/01/friend-request-movie-acquisition-freestyle-releasing-byron-allen-1201683226/|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=Deadline|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 22, 2017 || ''[[Hostiles (film)|Hostiles]]'' || [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]] || $40.9 million || <ref name=dl/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018 || March 9, 2018 || ''[[The Hurricane Heist]]'' || [[Rob Cohen]]  || $15.8 million || <ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/rob-cohen-the-hurricane-heist-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-motion-pictures-1202130540/|title=Rob Cohen's 'The Hurricane Heist' Acquired By Entertainment Studios|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Day|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 17, 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 6, 2018 || ''[[Chappaquiddick (film)|Chappaquiddick]]'' || [[John Curran (director)|John Curran]] || $18 million || <ref name=dl0>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/09/chappaquiddick-ted-kennedy-movie-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-toronto-film-festival-deal-1202164260/|title=Ted Kennedy Scandal Film 'Chappaquiddick' Lands $20M Commitment From Byron Allen At Toronto|last=Busch|first=Anita|last2=Fleming|first2=Mike|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=6|2019 || January 11, 2019 || ''[[Replicas (film)|Replicas]]'' || [[Jeffrey Nachmanoff]] || $8.1 million || <ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/09/keanu-reeves-replicas-byron-allen-toronto-film-festival-sale-entertainment-studios-4-million-dollars-1202164154/|title=Keanu Reeves' 'Replicas' First Big Toronto Deal: Byron Allen Pays $4 Million|last=Fleming|first=Mike|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| July 12, 2019 || ''Bethany Hamilton: Unstoppable'' || Aaron Lieber || || <ref>{{cite news|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Surfing Doc \u2018Bethany Hamilton: Unstoppable\u2019 Lands At Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/bethany-hamilton-unstoppable-release-date-documentary-entertainment-studios-motion-pictures-1202579928/|accessdate=March 21, 2019|work=Deadline|date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 16, 2019 || ''[[47 Meters Down: Uncaged]]'' || [[Johannes Roberts]] || $22.2 million || <ref>{{cite news|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Will Distribute Indie Sequel '48 Meters Down'|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-distribute-indie-sequel-48-meters-down-1202195349/|accessdate=December 26, 2017|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 20, 2019 || ''[[The Wedding Year]]'' || [[Robert Luketic]] || || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstshowing.net/2019/sarah-hyland-in-first-trailer-for-romantic-comedy-the-wedding-year/|title=Sarah Hyland in First Trailer for Romantic Comedy 'The Wedding Year'|website=First Showing|first=Alex|last=Billington|date=August 28, 2019|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 1, 2019 || ''[[Arctic Dogs]]'' || [[Aaron Woodley]] || $3.6 million || <ref>{{cite news|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|title=Byron Allen\u2019s ESMP Takes On U.S. Distribution Of Animation \u2018Arctic Dogs\u2019 Voiced By Jeremy Renner, Alec Baldwin|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/byron-allen-alec-baldwin-jeremy-renner-heidi-klum-esmp-distribution-arctic-dogs-justice-open-road-1202512695/|accessdate=December 3, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 22, 2019 || ''[[All Rise (film)|All Rise]]'' || [[Anthony Mandler]] || ||<ref>{{cite news|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Sundance Pic \u2018Monster\u2019 Gets New Title & Theatrical Deal With Byron Allen\u2019s ESMP|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/all-rise-movie-monster-release-date-byron-allen-1202599903/|accessdate=April 22, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| TBA || TBA ||''[[Boss Level]]'' || [[Joe Carnahan]] || ||<ref>{{cite news|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Bags Joe Carnahan's 'Boss Level' For U.S. Bow|url=http://deadline.com/2018/04/mel-gibson-boss-level-frank-grillo-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-release-date-1202365317/|accessdate=April 16, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://entertainmentstudios.com}}\n\n{{Film Studio}}\n{{The Weather Channel}}\n{{Fox Sports Networks}}\n\n[[Category:Entertainment Studios]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Television syndication distributors]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Entertainment Studios, Inc.\n| logo = Entertainment Studios Networks.png\n| former_name = CF Entertainment\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Television production]]<br>[[Broadcasting]]<br>[[Film distributor|Film distribution]]\n| founded = 1993\n| founder = [[Byron Allen]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Century City, Los Angeles|Century City]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| key_people = Byron Allen ([[chairman]], [[chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| assets = $1 billion\n| assets_year = 2017\n| owner = Allen Media\n| num_employees = 200\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| divisions = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Entertainment Studios#Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures|Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures]]\n* [[Entertainment Studios Networks]]\n}}\n| subsid = {{Plainlist|\n* [[#Allen Media Broadcasting|Allen Media Broadcasting]]\n* [[Freestyle Releasing]]\n* [[The Grio]]\n* [[The Weather Channel]]\n}}\n| website = {{url|entertainmentstudios.com}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"thr0\">{{cite news|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Byron Allen on \"Chasing Studio Crumbs,\" Weinstein's Future and Christian Bale's 'Hostiles'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/byron-allen-chasing-studio-crumbs-weinsteins-future-christian-bales-hostiles-1068759|accessdate=December 26, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 20, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Entertainment Studios\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-acquisition-the-weather-channel-tv-network-1202351426/|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Acquires The Weather Channel TV Network For $300 Million|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Fleming|first2=Mike|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Byron Allen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|title=Byron Allen Acquires The Weather Group in $300 Million Deal|last=Albiniak|first=Paige|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322203251/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|archive-date=March 22, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Entertainment Studios, Inc.''' is an American media and entertainment company based in [[Los Angeles]]. Owned and founded in 1993 by African-American comedian [[Byron Allen]], the company was initially involved in the production and distribution of first-run television series for [[United States|U.S.]] [[Broadcast syndication|television syndication]]. Under the [[Entertainment Studios Networks]] division, it also operates a group of [[digital cable]] and [[satellite television|satellite]] channels, which broadcast a mix of original programs and the company's syndicated content.\n\nIn the late 2010s, the company made several major expansions to its operations, including entering the [[film distribution]] market, acquiring [[The Weather Channel]] from [[NBCUniversal]] and [[Bain Capital]], partnering with [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] to acquire the [[regional sports network]] chain [[Fox Sports Networks]], and its acquisition of television stations from another minority-owned media group, [[Bayou City Broadcasting]].\n\n==History==\nEntertainment Studios was founded in 1993<ref name=dl2>{{cite news|last=Busch |first=Anita |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/byron-allen-acquires-indie-distribution-co-freestyle-releasing-1201591215/ |title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Acquires Indie Freestyle Releasing |publisher=Deadline |date=2015-10-22 |accessdate=2017-10-03}}</ref> as '''CF Entertainment''' by [[Byron Allen]].<ref name=bc>{{cite news |last1=Albiniak |first1=By Paige |title=CF Entertainment Gets New Name |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/cf-entertainment-gets-new-name-77234 |accessdate=October 5, 2019 |work=Broadcasting & Cable |date=December 12, 2003 |language=en-us}}</ref> The company was initially focused on producing low-cost, syndicated non-fiction programming, including interview series and [[court show]]s (largely scripted from actual testimony). Allen serves as host for some of these programs.<ref name=\"vty1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-still-very-acquisitive-1203117363/|title=Byron Allen Is Still 'Very Acquisitive' After Transformative Year|last=Marich|first=Robert|date=January 25, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> In December 2003, CF became Entertainment Studios.<ref name=bc/>\n\nEntertainment Studios greenlit its first film and stage projects in December 2011, when it acquired the rights to develop a [[biographical film]] and [[Play (theatre)|theatrical play]] on the life of [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]] from Davis' daughter with actor/singer, [[Tracey Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sammy-davis-jr-byron-allen-271544|title=Sammy Davis Jr. Biopic, Stage Show Planned|last=Block|first=Alex|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe company ventured into scripted programming in 2012, with the third-quarter launch of the sitcoms ''[[Mr. Box Office]]'' and ''[[The First Family (TV series)|The First Family]]''.<ref name=\"dl3\">{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Clears Syndicated Sitcom Block For Fall '12 Launch|url=http://deadline.com/2012/05/byron-allens-entertainment-studios-clears-syndicated-sitcom-block-for-fall-12-launch-276052/|accessdate=October 12, 2017|work=Deadline|date=May 21, 2012}}</ref> Both are set for 104 episodes<ref name=\"dl3\" /> over two years under a model of accelerated production similar to [[Debmar-Mercury]]'s [[Debmar-Mercury#The 10-90 Model|10-90 Model]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Comedy Series Starring Bill Bellamy Eying 100-Episode Order, Fall Launch|url=http://deadline.com/2012/05/comedy-series-starring-bill-bellamy-eying-100-episode-order-fall-launch-264598/|accessdate=October 12, 2017|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 3, 2012}}</ref> The two half hour shows were picked up as a two hour weekend primetime [[programming block]] with two episodes of each show back to back by [[Tribune Broadcasting|Tribune]], [[Weigel Broadcasting|Weigel]] and [[CBS Television Stations|CBS Television Station]] groups.<ref name=\"dl3\" /> The company launched its eighth cable channel and first ad-supported service, Justice Central.TV, on December 10, 2012.<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite web|last=Block|first=Alex Ben|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Launches Legal Digital Network|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/byron-allen-s-entertainment-studios-399843|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Entertainment Studios acquired [[Freestyle Releasing]] for an undisclosed amount \"said to be sealed for high-eight figures\". Freestyle also had an output deal with [[Netflix]].<ref name=dl2/> The Freestyle purchase was used to bolster an expansion into [[Film distributor|film distribution]], via its new Entertainment Studios Motion Pictures division.<ref name=\"wrap\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thewrap.com/inside-historic-sundance-bidding-war-for-birth-of-a-nation-why-netflix-offered-more-but-still-lost/|title=Inside Sundance Bidding War for 'Birth of a Nation'|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|date=January 26, 2016|work=The Wrap|accessdate=October 4, 2017|last2=Waxman|first2=Sharon}}</ref><ref name=\"HostilesInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/hostiles-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-47-meters-down-eddie-murphy-bob-weinstein-1202236594/|title='Hostiles' Distributor Byron Allen, On Growing A Movie Company In Difficult Times For Indies|last=Fleming|first=Mike|date=January 5, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> Its first release, ''[[47 Meters Down]]'', took in $44 million in box office revenue.<ref name=\"vty1\"/>\n\nAcross 2015, the company separately sued [[AT&T]], [[Comcast]] and [[Charter Communications]] for racial discrimination in being biased against minority run entertainment companies in not carrying its cable channels. AT&T settled in December with the addition of 7 of Entertainment Studios' channels added to AT&T's DirecTV line up. Entertainment Studios added similar suits against Charter and the FCC.<ref>{{cite news|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Files $10 Billion Discrimination Lawsuit Against Charter Communications, FCC|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-10-billion-discrimination-lawsuit-charter-fcc-1201691330/|accessdate=October 3, 2017|work=Variety|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref> The Comcast case, though initially dismissed at the district court, was allowed to go forward by the Ninth Circuit; Comcast was able to successfully petition the Supreme Court to hear its case in ''[[Comcast v. National Association of African-American-Owned Media]]'' during November 2019. The Charter case, also allowed to proceed by the Ninth Circuit, still has its petition pending at the Supreme Court.\n\nIn June 2016, Entertainment Studios acquired [[TheGrio]], a news website focusing on stories of interest to African Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/entertainment-studios-acquires-thegrio-1201772993/|title=Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Acquires TheGrio, African-American Focused Digital News Platform|last=Evans|first=Greg|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 15, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> In mid-September 2017, the company announced plans to launch an [[Over-the-top content|over the top]] sports streaming service known as Sports.tv.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lafayette|first=Jon|title=Entertainment Studios to Launch Streaming OTT Sports Platform|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/entertainment-studios-launch-streaming-ott-sports-platform/168737|accessdate=October 4, 2017|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2018, Entertainment Studios announced its intent to acquire [[The Weather Channel]]'s television assets from an [[NBCUniversal]]/[[Bain Capital]]/[[Blackstone Group]] partnership. The actual value was undisclosed, but was reported to be around $300 million; the channel's [[The Weather Company|non-television assets]], which were separately sold to IBM two years prior, were not included in the sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|title=Byron Allen Acquires The Weather Group in $300 Million Deal|last=Albiniak|first=Paige|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322203251/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/currency/byron-allen-acquires-weather-group-300-million-deal/172512|archive-date=March 22, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Entertainment Studios announced that it had arranged $500 million worth of [[Line of credit|credit facilities]] through [[Deutsche Bank]] Securities, Jefferies Financial Group, Brightwood Capital Advisors and [[Comerica]]. Allen explained that these funds were to be used for further \"large-scale\" acquisitions, productions, and other general expenses.<ref name=\"vty1\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Byron Allen Announces $500M In Credit Facility For Entertainment Studios Expansion|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/byron-allen-entertainment-studios-500-million-credit-facilities-expansion-1202456572/|accessdate=September 17, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 4, 2018}}</ref> In an interview with ''Variety'', Allen stated that he was \"not a seller\", and that he was \"one or two acquisitions away from being a fairly large company\".<ref name=\"vty1\"/> On May 3, 2019, it was announced that, under the subsidiary Diamond Sports Group, Entertainment Studios would be an equity and content partner in [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]'s acquisition of [[Fox Sports Networks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/sinclair-disney-regional-sports-network-deal-1203204685/|title=Sinclair Clinches Disney-Regional Sports Networks Deal, Byron Allen Joins as Partner|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=May 3, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn May 6, 2019, Entertainment Studios announced that it would expand into television station ownership by acquiring the stations of [[Bayou City Broadcasting]] for $165 million, including Evansville, Indiana's [[WEVV-TV]] and [[WEEV-LD]], and Lafayette, Louisiana's [[KADN-TV]] and [[KLAF-LD]]. The stations will operate under the new unit, Allen Media Broadcasting.<ref name=vty0>{{cite web|last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |title=Byron Allen Expands Into Broadcasting, Buys 4 TV Stations for $165 Million |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/byron-allen-buys-tv-stations-165-milion-1203205894/ |accessdate=May 6, 2019|work=Variety|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> The sale was completed on July 31, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Wes |title=FCC Approves Evansville TV Station Sale |url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/story/40860316/fcc-approves-evansville-tv-station-sale |accessdate=August 8, 2019 |work=Inside Indiana Business |publisher=Grow INdiana Media Ventures, LLC |date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> On October 1, 2019, Allen Media agreed to purchase 11 stations from [[Heartland Media|USA Television]] for $290 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lafayette |first1=Jon |title=Allen\u2019s Entertainment Studios Buying USA Stations for $290M |url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/allens-entertainment-studios-buying-usa-stations-for-290m |accessdate=October 1, 2019 |work=Broadcasting & Cable |publisher=Future Publishing Limited |date=October 1, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref> The sale of the Heartland stations was approved by the FCC on November 22, 2019, <ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/1810966.pdf \"Notice of Consent to Transfer of Control\"], ''CDBS Public Access'', [[Federal Communications Commission]], 22 November 2019, Retrieved 27 November 2019.</ref> and it was completed on February 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Anita |title=Byron Allen\u2019s Entertainment Studios Acquires 11 Local TV Stations For $305 Million |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/byron-allens-entertainment-studios-expands-broadcast-holdings-with-purchase-of-11-tv-stations-for-305-million-1202858008/ |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |work=Deadline |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Television series distributed by Entertainment Studios==\n===Court shows===\n*''[[America's Court with Judge Ross]]''\n*''[[Justice for All with Judge Cristina P\u00e9rez]]''\n*''[[Mablean Ephriam|Justice with Judge Mablean]]''\n*''Supreme Justice with Judge Karen''\n*''[[Glenda Hatchett|The Verdict with Judge Hatchett]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/entertainment-studios-orders-130-more-episodes-of-all-five-of-its-court-shows-1202472098/|title=Entertainment Studios Orders 130 More Episodes For Each Of Its Five Court Shows|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref> <!-- sourcing all court shows -->\n*''[[We the People With Gloria Allred]]'' (2011-2012)\n\n===Sitcoms===\n*''[[The First Family (TV series)|The First Family]]'' (September 2012\u2013April 25, 2015) syndicated (April 19, 2013\u2013 ) [[BET Her]]\n*''[[Mr. Box Office]]'' (September 2012\u2013April 25, 2015) syndicated (April 19, 2013\u2013 ) BET Her<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bet-networks-nabs-two-sitcoms-433046|title=BET Networks Nabs Two Sitcoms in Multimillion-Dollar Reverse-Syndication Deal|last=Block|first=Alex|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 4, 2013|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Game shows===\n*''[[Funny You Should Ask (2017 game show)|Funny You Should Ask]]''\n*''[[Who Wants to Date a Comedian?]]''\n\n===Syndicated specials===\n*''Comedy Jam''\n*''Feel the Beat''\n*''Happy Holidays America''\n*''We Have a Dream''\n\n===Talk and magazine series===\n*''Beautiful Homes & Great Estates''\n*''Career Day''\n*''[[Comics Unleashed with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Designers, Fashions & Runways''\n*''[[Entertainers with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Global Business People''\n*''The Gossip Queens''\n*''Latin Lifestyles''\n*''[[Kickin' It with Byron Allen]]''\n*''Urban Style''\n*''The Writer's Hot List''\n*''[[The Young Icons]]''\n\n===Other shows===\n*''[[The American Athlete]]''\n\n== Entertainment Studios Networks ==\n{{Main|Entertainment Studios Networks}}\n\n===Cable and Digital===\n*''Automotive.TV''\n*''Cars.TV''\n*''Comedy.TV''\n*''ES.TV''<ref name=\"dl1\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/07/anchor-bay-byron-allen-entertainment-studios-multi-year-deal-1201786756/|title=Anchor Bay And Byron Allen's Entertainment Studios Join In Multi-Year Deal|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=July 14, 2016|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n*''MyDestination.TV''\n*''Pets.TV''\n*''Recipe.TV''<ref name=dl1/>\n\n===Television channels===\n*Justice Central, launched December 10, 2012 on AT&T U-verse's family tier which is also its first advertising support only channel.<ref name=thr/>\n* Weather network\n**[[The Weather Channel]]\n**[[Weatherscan]]\n**[[Local Now]]\n\n==Allen Media Broadcasting==\nAllen Media Broadcasting, LLC is a TV station operating company owned by Entertainment Studios.\n\nOn May 6, 2019, Entertainment Studios announced that it would expand into television station ownership by acquiring the stations of [[Bayou City Broadcasting]] for $165 million, including Evansville, Indiana's [[WEVV-TV]] and [[WEEV-LD]], and Lafayette, Louisiana's [[KADN-TV]] and [[KLAF-LD]]. The stations will operate under the new division Allen Media Broadcasting.<ref name=vty0/> Allen Media made an offer for [[TEGNA]] TV station group as the third know bidder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Byron Allen Makes Acquisition Offer for Tegna Station Group |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/byron-allen-tegna-acquisition-bid-1203531539/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Variety |date=March 12, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Television stations===\nStations are arranged in alphabetical order by state and [[city of license]].\n\n'''Note:'''\n* ('''##''') - ''Indicates stations that were previously owned by [[Bayou City Broadcasting]], prior to its acquisition by Allen Media in 2019.''\n* ('''\u00a7\u00a7''') - ''Indicates stations that were previously owned by [[Heartland Media]], prior to its acquisition by Allen Media in 2020.''\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| [[City of license]] / [[Media market|Market]]\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"| S