{"title_page": "2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox sports competition event\n| event       = Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay\n| competition = 2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships\n| image       =\n| caption     = \n| venue       = [[Arena Birmingham]]\n| dates       = 3\u20134 March\n| competitors = 40\n| nations     = 10\n| win_value   = 3:01.77 '''[[List of world records in athletics#Indoor world records|WIR]]'''\n| gold        = [[Karol Zalewski]]<br />[[Rafa\u0142 Omelko]]<br />[[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]]<br />[[Jakub Krzewina]]<br />[[Patryk Adamczyk]]*\n| goldNOC     = POL\n| silver      = [[Fred Kerley]]<br />[[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]]<br />[[Aldrich Bailey Jr.]]<br />[[Vernon Norwood]]<br />[[Marqueze Washington]]*<br />[[Paul Dedewo]]*\n| silverNOC   = USA\n| bronze      = [[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]]<br />[[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]]<br />[[Jonathan Sacoor]]<br />[[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]]\n| bronzeNOC   = BEL\n| prev        = [[2016 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|2016]]\n| next        = [[2020 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|2020]]\n}}\n{{2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships}}\nThe '''men's [[4 \u00d7 400 metres relay]]''' at the [[2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships]] took place on 3 and 4 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-indoor-championships/iaaf-world-indoor-championships-6019/results/men/4x400-metres-relay/final/startlist#resultheader |title=IAAF World Indoor Championships Timetable |access-date=March 16, 2016 |work=IAAF}}</ref><ref>[https://media.aws.iaaf.org/competitiondocuments/pdf/6019/AT-4X4-M-h----.SL2.pdf Start list]</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nIn the heats, the Dominican Republic rested their star, disqualified silver medalist [[Luguel\u00edn Santos]].  They didn't qualify and Santos did not get to run the final.  Similarly, USA was able to rest their stars, [[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]] and [[Aldrich Bailey]] while successfully qualifying for the final.\nIn the final, USA was out fast with [[Fred Kerley]] having a marginal edge at the break, but extending it by running an efficient tangent from lane 6, netting himself a 3-metre lead over Poland's [[Karol Zalewski]].  Zalewski kept that gap for most of the second lap, losing a little ground in the handoff.  Kerley's split 44.84.  The Borl\u00e9e brothers, represented by [[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]], representing [[Belgium]] were an equal gap back.  With an efficient handoff to [[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]], USA gained another 3 metres.  Through the second leg, Rafa\u0142 Omelko chipped away at Cherry's lead, by the time the handoff took place, the gap between USA and Poland was back to 3 metres.  Behind them, [[Jereem Richards]] brought Trinidad and Tobago past [[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]] and approached passing Omelko before fading back.  Cherry's split was 45.39.  The third leg for USA was [[Aldrich Bailey]], vs Poland's [[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]], Bailey lost another meter as Poland, Trinidad and Tobago and Belgium gained.  Bailey's split 46.10.  After taking the baton, USA's [[Vernon Norwood]] accelerated to open another metre.  Behind him, Poland's [[Jakub Krzewina]] led the pursuers, with TTO's [[Lalonde Gordon]] and Belgium's [[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]] in close order.  By the end of the first lap, Norwood had extended the lead to 5 metres, but down the final backstretch, the lead began to shrink.  Coming off the final turn, Krzewina had a burst of speed, Norwood straightened up and tightened up, Krzewina went by.  Five metres back Borl\u00e9e was attempting a similar move on Gordon, without as much authority.  In a tight battle for bronze, Borl\u00e9e was able to outlearn Gordon.\n\nPoland's winning time was a new [[List of world records in athletics#Indoor|world indoor record]], beating USA's team from four years earlier.  The final split was timed at 45.44 from when Norwood crossed the line, but considering he made up at least three metres, Krzewina's time was considerably faster.  Behind them, [[List of Belgian records in athletics#Indoor|Belgium]] and [[List of Trinidad and Tobago records in athletics#Indoor|Trinidad and Tobago]] set national records.\n\n==Results==\n===Heats===\nThe heats were started on 3 March at 12:32.<ref>[https://media.aws.iaaf.org/competitiondocuments/pdf/6019/AT-4X4-M-h----.RS6.pdf Heats results]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Rank !! Heat !! Lane !! Nation !! Athletes !! Time !! Notes\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| 1 || 2 || 6 || align=left|{{USA}} || align=left|[[Fred Kerley]], [[Marqueze Washington]], [[Paul Dedewo]], [[Vernon Norwood]] || 3:04.00 || Q\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| 2 || 1 || 6 || align=left|{{BEL}} || align=left|[[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]], [[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]], [[Jonathan Sacoor]], [[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]] || 3:05.22 || Q, SB\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| 3 || 1 || 5 || align=left|{{POL}} || align=left|[[Karol Zalewski]], [[Patryk Adamczyk]], [[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]], [[Jakub Krzewina]] || 3:05.24 || Q, SB\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| 4 || 2 || 5 || align=left|{{GBR2}} || align=left|[[Owen Smith (athlete)|Owen Smith]], [[Sebastian Rodger]], [[Jamal Rhoden-Stevens]], [[Grant Plenderleith]] || 3:05.29 || Q, SB\n|- bgcolor=ddffdd\n| 5 || 1 || 3 || align=left|{{TTO}} || align=left|[[Renny Quow]], [[Jereem Richards]], [[Machel Cedenio]], [[Lalonde Gordon]] || 3:05.96 || q, SB\n|- bgcolor=ddffdd\n| 6 || 1 || 4 || align=left|{{CZE}} || align=left|[[Michal Desensk\u00fd]], [[V\u00edt M\u00fcller]], [[Filip \u0160nejdr]], [[Patrik \u0160orm]] || 3:06.40 || q, SB\n|-\n| 7 || 2 || 2 || align=left|{{ESP}} || align=left|[[Lucas B\u00faa]], [[Manuel Guijarro (athlete)|Manuel Guijarro]], [[Aleix Porras]], [[Samuel Garc\u00eda]] || 3:07.52 || SB\n|-\n| 8 || 2 || 3 || align=left|{{DOM}} || align=left|[[Juander Santos]], [[Raymond Urbino]], [[Andito Charles]], [[Leonel Bon\u00f3n]] || 3:10.45 || SB\n|-\n| {{hs|9}} || 1 || 2 || align=left|{{UKR}} || align=left| || {{sort|9:99.99|DNS}} ||\n|-\n| {{hs|9}} || 2 || 4 || align=left|{{JAM}} || align=left| || {{sort|9:99.99|DNS}} ||\n|}\n\n===Final===\n[[File:WK040315 finale 4x400m heren dylan.jpg|thumb|The first leg of the final]]\n[[File:WK040411pools 4x400m herenteam.jpg|thumb|The winning Polish team]]\nThe final was started on 4 March at 15:58.<ref>[https://media.aws.iaaf.org/competitiondocuments/pdf/6019/AT-4X4-M-f----.RS6.pdf Final results]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Rank !! Lane !! Nation !! Athletes !! Time !! Notes\n|-\n| {{gold1}} || 4 || align=left|{{POL}} || align=left|[[Karol Zalewski]], [[Rafa\u0142 Omelko]], [[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]], [[Jakub Krzewina]] || 3:01.77 || '''[[List of world records in athletics#Indoor world records|WIR]]'''\n|-\n| {{silver2}} || 6 || align=left|{{USA}} || align=left|[[Fred Kerley]], [[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]], [[Aldrich Bailey Jr.]], [[Vernon Norwood]] || 3:01.97 || {{AthAbbr|SB}}<ref>Although the performance by the US team was better than the official former world record, it was marginally slower than the official [[List of United States records in track and field|US record]] of 3:01.96 which was not ratified by IAAF as it did not fulfill its anti-doping requirements.</ref>\n|-\n| {{bronze3}} || 5 || align=left|{{BEL}} || align=left|[[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]], [[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]], [[Jonathan Sacoor]], [[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]] || 3:02.51 || '''[[List of Belgian records in athletics#Indoor|NIR]]'''\n|-\n| 4 || 1 || align=left|{{TTO}} || align=left|[[Deon Lendore]], [[Jereem Richards]], [[Asa Guevara]], [[Lalonde Gordon]] || 3:02.52 || '''[[List of Trinidad and Tobago records in athletics#Indoor|NIR]]'''\n|-\n| 5 || 2 || align=left|{{CZE}} || align=left|[[Michal Desensk\u00fd]], [[Patrik \u0160orm]], [[Filip \u0160nejdr]], [[Pavel Masl\u00e1k]] || 3:04.87 || {{AthAbbr|SB}}\n|-\n| 6 || 3 || align=left|{{GBR2}} || align=left|[[Owen Smith (athlete)|Owen Smith]], [[Grant Plenderleith]], [[Jamal Rhoden-Stevens]], [[Lee Thompson (sprinter)|Lee Thompson]] || 3:05.08 || {{AthAbbr|SB}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{WIC4x400mRelay}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2018 Iaaf World Indoor Championships - Men's 4 x 400 metres relay}}\n[[Category:2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships|4 \u00d7 400 metres relay]]\n[[Category:4 \u00d7 400 metres relay at the World Athletics Indoor Championships]]\n[[Category:2018 in men's athletics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox sports competition event\n| event       = Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay\n| competition = 2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships\n| image       =\n| caption     = \n| venue       = [[Arena Birmingham]]\n| dates       = 3\u20134 March\n| competitors = 40\n| nations     = 10\n| win_value   = 3:01.77 '''[[List of world records in athletics#Indoor world records|WIR]]'''\n| gold        = [[Karol Zalewski]]<br />[[Rafa\u0142 Omelko]]<br />[[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]]<br />[[Jakub Krzewina]]<br />[[Patryk Adamczyk]]*\n| goldNOC     = POL\n| silver      = [[Fred Kerley]]<br />[[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]]<br />[[Aldrich Bailey Jr.]]<br />[[Vernon Norwood]]<br />[[Marqueze Washington]]*<br />[[Paul Dedewo]]*\n| silverNOC   = USA\n| bronze      = [[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]]<br />[[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]]<br />[[Jonathan Sacoor]]<br />[[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]]\n| bronzeNOC   = BEL\n| prev        = [[2016 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|2016]]\n| next        = [[2020 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|2020]]\n}}\n{{2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships}}\nThe '''men's [[4 \u00d7 400 metres relay]]''' at the [[2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships]] took place on 3 and 4 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-indoor-championships/iaaf-world-indoor-championships-6019/results/men/4x400-metres-relay/final/startlist#resultheader |title=IAAF World Indoor Championships Timetable |access-date=March 16, 2016 |work=IAAF}}</ref><ref>[https://media.aws.iaaf.org/competitiondocuments/pdf/6019/AT-4X4-M-h----.SL2.pdf Start list]</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nIn the heats, the Dominican Republic rested their star, disqualified silver medalist [[Luguel\u00edn Santos]].  They didn't qualify and Santos did not get to run the final.  Similarly, USA was able to rest their stars, [[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]] and [[Aldrich Bailey]] while successfully qualifying for the final.\nIn the final, USA was out fast with [[Fred Kerley]] having a marginal edge at the break, but extending it by running an efficient tangent from lane 6, netting himself a 3 metre lead over Poland's [[Karol Zalewski]].  Zalewski kept that gap for most of the second lap, losing a little ground in the handoff.  Kerley's split 44.84.  The Borl\u00e9e brothers, represented by [[Dylan Borl\u00e9e]], representing [[Belgium]] were an equal gap back.  With an efficient handoff to [[Michael Cherry (athlete)|Michael Cherry]], USA gained another 3 metres.  Through the second leg, Rafa\u0142 Omelko chipped away at Cherry's lead, by the time the handoff took place, the gap between USA and Poland was back to 3 metres.  Behind them, [[Jereem Richards]] brought Trinidad and Tobago past [[Jonathan Borl\u00e9e]] and approached passing Omelko before fading back.  Cherry's split was 45.39.  The third leg for USA was [[Aldrich Bailey]], vs Poland's [[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]], Bailey lost another meter as Poland, Trinidad and Tobago and Belgium gained.  Bailey's split 46.10.  After taking the baton, USA's [[Vernon Norwood]] accelerated to open another metre.  Behind him, Poland's [[Jakub Krzewina]] led the pursuers, with TTO's [[Lalonde Gordon]] and Belgium's [[Kevin Borl\u00e9e]] in close order.  By the end of the first lap, Norwood had extended the lead to 5 metres, but down the final backstr